${\footnote Confirmation Dialog}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Confirmation Dialog;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20517.bmp\} Confirmation Dialog\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Dialogs}{\v 20516}\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20517.bmp\} \b \i confirmation dialog \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20519.bmp\} \b \i caption \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20518.bmp\} \b \i text \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20520.bmp\} \b \i icon \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20521.bmp\} \b \i buttons \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20522.bmp\} \b \i default button \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i confirmation dialog \i0 \b0 serves to select further operation by the user, e.g. for displaying a message.\par
\par
As the first parameter the text is entered which will be displayed in the dialog window caption (upper bar).\par
\par
The second parameter is the text which will be displayed in the dialog window. The text may include several lines, the window dimensions will be adapted to the line number and length. A multi-line text can be defined either by textual linking of single-line text constants and of the next line constants, or a multi-line text can be created in the text variable.\par
\par
By means of the third parameter the icon to be displayed can be selected. This icon is selected by specifying the numeric value in the range from 0 to 4:\par
\tab 0 = none\par
\tab 1 = error message\par
\tab 2 = question\par
\tab 3 = warning\par
\tab 4 = information\par
\par
By means of the fourth parameter the set of the buttons to be displayed is selected, specifying the numeric value between 0 and 5:\par
\tab 0 = OK\par
\tab 1 = OK / Cancel\par
\tab 2 = Abort / Retry / Ignore\par
\tab 3 = Yes / No / Cancel\par
\tab 4 = Yes / No\par
\tab 5 = Retry / Cancel\par
\par
The last parameter is again a numeric one. It indicates, which button will be preset as a default one. The value is specified in the range between 1 and 3.\par
\par
After selecting some of the button the confirmation dialog window will return a numeric value according to the button selected:\par
\tab 1 = OK\par
\tab 2 = Cancel\par
\tab 3 = Abort\par
\tab 4 = Retry\par
\tab 5 = Ignore\par
\tab 6 = Yes\par
\tab 7 = No\par
\par
If the return of a selected button value is not required, then the confirmation dialog may be also used as a command.\par
\page

